                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/10/durham-officials-raise-concerns-after-dpd-firing" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2009/10/durham-officials-raise-concerns-after-dpd-firing&amp;text=Durham officials raise concerns after DPD firing" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=Durham%20officials%20raise%20concerns%20after%20DPD%20firing%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2009%2F10%2Fdurham-officials-raise-concerns-after-dpd-firing" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>A Durham Police Department employee&rsquo;s recent termination over excessive overtime pay has raised concerns about a lack of oversight.</p>
<p>During a year in which the alleged overtime abuse took place, several employees at both the City of Durham and DPD questioned how a non-uniformed employee was earning overtime compensation that more than doubled her regular salary. Several attempts to shine a light on the situation were ignored by senior officials at the police department, said City Council member Eugene Brown.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m angry about this,&rdquo; Brown said. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m upset about this and what makes me particularly angry about this is the fact that this was not dealt with when brought to the police department&rsquo;s attention.&rdquo;</p>
<p>According to an audit released by Durham&rsquo;s Audit Services Department, Alesha Robinson-Taylor, a secondary employment coordinator at DPD, earned $62,583.13 in overtime pay between September 2008 and August 2009. When concerns about the legitimacy of Robinson-Taylor&rsquo;s overtime were voiced, the mechanisms within DPD and the city to address the concerns proved ineffective.</p>
<p>Durham City Manager Tom Bonfield said the leadership within the police department failed on several occasions to adequately respond to the claims of abuse when it was brought to their attention.</p>
<p>&ldquo;This situation with the audit finding... is of extra concern for us,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;It is particularly troubling that this was going on while we were in the midst of budget cuts and when we had to eliminate 113 positions, many of them were police officers.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Nearly all of Robinson-Taylor&rsquo;s overtime compensation was approved by Deputy Police Chief B.J. Council. Council will retire Dec. 31.</p>
<p>DPD Public Information Officer Kammie Michael declined to comment, referring The Chronicle to the city manager&rsquo;s office.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>Bonfield said he is not concerned by the department&rsquo;s decision to allow Council to retire, noting that the decision is common when an employee has a long-standing tenure within any company or organization.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In the case of a senior person who had worked for the city for 20 years, you certainly have to make a change in leadership, but I don&rsquo;t think you need to punish the entirety of their career,&rdquo; he said.</p>
<p>Robinson-Taylor&rsquo;s immediate supervisor, Capt. Charlene Balch, noticed the excessive overtime and brought it to the attention of Council. In response, Council relieved Balch of her duties approving Robinson-Taylor&rsquo;s overtime pay and instead approved it herself.</p>
<p>&ldquo;In essence, Charlene was the whistle-blower, but her whistle was taken from her by B.J. Council,&rdquo; Brown said.</p>
                            
    
<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="c4087a59c7">
    <h3>Get The Chronicle straight to your inbox</h3>
    <p>Signup for our editorially curated, weekly newsletter. Cancel at any time.</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <form action="//dukechronicle.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe/post?u=c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b&amp;id=c4087a59c7" method="post">
